010/**
011 * Allows for the use of custom colors with custom names.
012 * <p>
013 * These colors are comparable for equality but the ordering of them is based on
014 * their hex values.
015 * <p>
016 * Has some built in palettes available as SColor arrays.
017 *
018 * @author Eben Howard - http://squidpony.com - howard@squidpony.com
019 * @see SquidColorCenter Another way to manage colors if you don't want to use preallocated instances.
020 */
021public class SColor extends Color {

6410    /**
6411     * An array of SColor values that should all be fairly different from any other in the group.
6412     * This may be useful for tinting things that should be color-coded differently from each other. To get a random
6413     * order for these colors while still guaranteeing that no color will be drawn twice in the first 56 choices, you
6414     * can use {@code OrderedSet<SColor> palette = new OrderedSet<SColor>(SColor.VARIED_PALETTE).shuffle(rng);} (where
6415     * rng is any non-null RNG) and then get sequential colors from that set with
6416     * {@code int i = 0; SColor color = palette.getAt(i);} , incrementing i before calling getAt again and possibly
6417     * wrapping with {@code i %= 56;} .
6418     * This includes 56 colors, organized in groups of 4 from dark to light in each group:
6419     * <ul>
6420     *     <li>0-3: gray group</li>
6421     *     <li>4-7: brown group</li>
6422     *     <li>8-11: red group</li>
6423     *     <li>12-15: pink group</li>
6424     *     <li>16-19: magenta/purple group</li>
6425     *     <li>20-23: purple/blue-ish group</li>
6426     *     <li>24-27: darker blue group</li>
6427     *     <li>28-31: lighter blue and blue-green group</li>
6428     *     <li>32-35: pure green group</li>
6429     *     <li>36-39: grayish-green group</li>
6430     *     <li>40-43: yellow-green group</li>
6431     *     <li>44-47: yellow group</li>
6432     *     <li>48-51: orange group</li>
6433     *     <li>52-55: orange-red-pink/salmon/coral group</li>
6434     * </ul>
6435     */
6436    public static final SColor[] VARIED_PALETTE = {
6437            DARK_GRAY, GRAY, LIGHT_GRAY, DB_EGGSHELL,
6438            DB_SEAL_BROWN, BROWNER, DARK_TAN, TAN,
6439            DB_BLOOD, PURE_CRIMSON, RED, IBIS_WING,
6440            TREE_PEONY, DEEP_CERISE, HOT_PINK, PINK,
6441            INDIGO, PURPLE, PSYCHEDELIC_PURPLE, LIGHT_VIOLET,
6442            ROYAL_PURPLE, VIOLET, HALF_PURPLE, LAVENDER_FLORAL,
6443            COBALT, CERULEAN_BLUE, BLUE, CORNFLOWER_BLUE,
6444            LIGHT_BLUE_FLOWER, ROBIN_EGG_BLUE, CYAN, LIGHT_BLUE,
6445            GREEN_BAMBOO, PERSIAN_GREEN, ELECTRIC_GREEN, MINT_GREEN,
6446            CAMO_GREEN, PALE_GREEN_ONION, PASTEL_GREEN, MOSS_GREEN,
6447            OLIVE_DRAB, YELLOW_GREEN, CHARTREUSE_GREEN, ELECTRIC_LIME,
6448            GOLD, SCHOOL_BUS_YELLOW, YELLOW, LEMON_CHIFFON,
6449            BURNT_ORANGE, OCHRE, CAPE_JASMINE, PEACH_YELLOW,
6450            SAFETY_ORANGE, CORAL_DYE, DARK_SALMON, LIGHT_YELLOW_DYE

6639    /**
6640     * A constructor with no passed values. Builds a white (opaque all channels)
6641     * object.
6642     */
6643    public SColor() { //builds white
6644        this(Color.rgb888(Color.WHITE));
6645    }
6646
6647    /**
6648     * Creates a new color that's the same value as the passed in color.
6649     *
6650     * @param color
6651     */
6652    public SColor(Color color) {
6653        this(Color.rgb888(color));
6654    }
6655
6656    /**
6657     * Creates a new color that's the same value as the passed in color and
6658     * given the provided name.
6659     *
6660     * @param color
6661     * @param name
6662     */
6663    public SColor(Color color, String name) {
6664        this(Color.rgb888(color));
6665        this.name = name;
6666    }
6667
6668    /**
6669     * Creates a new color that has the given combined RGB value.
6670     *
6671     * @param colorValue
6672     */
6673    public SColor(int colorValue) {
6674        super((colorValue << 8) | 255);
6675        name = super.toString();
6676    }
6677
6678    /**
6679     * Creates a new color that has the given combined RGB value and the
6680     * provided name.
6681     *
6682     * @param colorValue
6683     * @param name
6684     */
6685    public SColor(int colorValue, String name) {
6686        super((colorValue << 8) | 255);
6687        this.name = name;
6688    }
6689
6690    /**
6691     * Creates a new color that has the given RGB values.
6692     *
6693     * @param r
6694     * @param g
6695     * @param b
6696     */
6697    public SColor(int r, int g, int b) {
6698        super(r / 255f, g / 255f, b / 255f, 1.0f);
6699        name = super.toString();
6700    }
6701
6702    /**
6703     * Creates a new color that has the given ARGB values.
6704     *
6705     * @param r
6706     * @param g
6707     * @param b
6708     * @param a
6709     */
6710    public SColor(int r, int g, int b, int a) {
6711        super(r / 255f, g / 255f, b / 255f, a / 255f);
6712        name = super.toString();
6713    }
6714
6715    /**
6716     * Creates a new color that has the given RGB values and the provided name.
6717     *
6718     * @param r

6764    /**
6765     * Use {@link #intToFloatColor(int)} instead, it's twice as fast on desktop, but still 3x slower than the JDK method
6766     * {@link Float#intBitsToFloat(int)}. {@link com.badlogic.gdx.utils.NumberUtils#intToFloatColor(int)} is now
6767     * super-sourced on GWT with a drastically simpler replacement than the original GWT code, and will use the JDK's
6768     * implementation on desktop where it is much faster, so using NumberUtils should be the way to go.
6769     * @param bits the int to convert to float; only bits in the mask 0xfeffffff will be used
6770     * @return the float that can be used to represent the given bits
6771     */
6772    public static float intToFloatColorAlt(final int bits)
6773    {
6774        return (1f - (bits >>> 30 & 2)) * (0x1.0p0f + 0x0.000002p0f * (bits & 0x7fffff)) *
6775                ((bits & 0x40000000) == 0
6776                        ? (((bits >> 29 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-64f) * ((bits >> 28 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-32f) * ((bits >> 27 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-16f) * ((bits >> 26 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-8f) * ((bits >> 25 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-4f) * 0x1.0p-2f * ((bits >> 23 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-1f))
6777                        : (((bits >> 29 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p64f : 1) * ((bits >> 28 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p32f : 1) * ((bits >> 27 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p16f : 1) * ((bits >> 26 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p8f : 1) * ((bits >> 25 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p4f : 1) * 0x1.0p2f * ((bits >> 23 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-1f))
6778                );
6779    }
6780    /**
6781     * Possible replacement for {@link NumberUtils#intToFloatColor(int)} that is much less complex on GWT; shouldn't be
6782     * called directly and you should default to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.utils.NumberUtils#intToFloatColor(int)}. That
6783     * method is now super-sourced on GWT with a this method as a much simpler replacement for the original GWT code,
6784     * but will not replace the JDK's implementation on desktop where it is much faster. Using NumberUtils should be the
6785     * way to go. For reference, see GWT's source for {@link Float#intBitsToFloat(int)},
6786     * https://gwt.googlesource.com/gwt/+/2.8.0/user/super/com/google/gwt/emul/java/lang/Float.java#96 ,
6787     * which involves multiple if statements, temporary variables, creates a long (slow on GWT), and finally passes off
6788     * control to another method. There's also {@link #rgbToFloatColor(int)} if you don't need to worry about alpha.
6789     *
6790     * @param bits the int to convert to float; only bits in the mask 0xfeffffff will be used
6791     * @return the float that can be used to represent the given bits
6792     */
6793    public static float intToFloatColor(final int bits)
6794    {
6795        return (1 - (bits >>> 30 & 2)) * (1f + 0x0.000002p0f * (bits & 0x7fffff)) *
6796                multipliers[(bits >> 24 & 0x7e) | (bits >> 23 & 1)];
6797    }
6798    public static float rgbToFloatColor(final int rgb)
6799    {
6800        return -(0x1.0p125f + 0x0.000002p125f * (rgb & 0x7fffff)) * ((rgb >> 23 & 1) + 1);
6801    }
6802
6803    /**
6804     * Modifies the color parameter {@code changing} so its value is the one encoded in {@code value}. The way to
6805     * obtain value for libGDX Color objects is with {@link Color#toFloatBits()}, which uses ABGR order, so this
6806     * does some quick work to convert that to RGBA order and assign that into changing.
6807     * @param changing a Color object that will be modified to have the given value
6808     * @param value a value as a float that can be obtained by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
6809     * @return
6810     */
6811    public static Color colorFromFloat(Color changing, float value)
6812    {
6813        return changing.set(Integer.reverseBytes(NumberUtils.floatToIntColor(value)));
6814    }
6815    static final char[] digits = {
6816            '0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7',
6817            '8', '9', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F'};
6818
6819    /**
6820     * Stores the value of color in the char[] {@code changing}, using RGBA8888 format with two hex digits per channel.
6821     * This means that changing must be at least length 8 (this doesn't check for efficiency reasons), and that the
6822     * first two chars represent the red channel from 0 to 255, then the next two are green, then blue. The alpha
6823     * channel is a special case because it represents alpha values between 0 and 254, and effectively rounds down to
6824     * the nearest even number if an odd number value was somehow given to it. For example, opaque white will be shown
6825     * as "FFFFFFFE", and pure red with 50% alpha will be shown as "FF00007E".
6826     * <br>
6827     * The value of {@code color} should be the same type used internally in libGDX and SquidLib, that is, an ABGR
6828     * packed float that could be passed directly to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)}.
6829     *
6830     * @param changing a char array that will be changed in place; must not be null and must have length of at least 8
6831     * @param color a color
6832     * @return
6833     */
6834    public static char[] floatToChars(final char[] changing, final float color)
6835    {
6836        final int i = NumberUtils.floatToIntColor(color);
6837        changing[1] = digits[i & 15];
6838        changing[0] = digits[(i >>> 4) & 15];
6839        changing[3] = digits[(i >>> 8) & 15];
6840        changing[2] = digits[(i >>> 12) & 15];
6841        changing[5] = digits[(i >>> 16) & 15];
6842        changing[4] = digits[(i >>> 20) & 15];
6843        changing[7] = digits[(i >>> 24) & 14]; // mask is 14 due to libGDX avoiding floats that can be NaN
6844        changing[6] = digits[i >>> 28];
6845        return changing;
6846    }
6847
6848    /**
6849     * Meant for usage with {@link #floatToChars(char[], float)}, this will take 8 chars from {@code data} and use them
6850     * to construct an int in RGBA8888 format. Some parts of libGDX use and expect RGBA8888 order, such as most
6851     * constructors for Color and {@link Color#set(int)}, while others use ABGR8888 (often with packed floats), like
6852     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)}, which is the fastest and least wasteful way to set
6853     * the current color used by a Batch for tinting.
6854     * @param data a char array that must not be null and must have length of at least 8
6855     * @param offset where to start reading from in data; there must be at least 8 items between offset and data.length
6856     * @return an int in RGBA8888 format
6857     */
6858    public static int charsToRGBA(final char[] data, final int offset)
6859    {
6860        return StringKit.intFromHex(data, offset, Math.min(data.length, offset+8));
6861    }

6925     * constructors for Color and {@link Color#set(int)}, while others use ABGR8888 (often with packed floats), like

6939    /**
6940     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 4 RGBA float components. LibGDX expects ABGR format
6941     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
6942     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
6943     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
6944     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
6945     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
6946     * @param r a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for red
6947     * @param g a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for green
6948     * @param b a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for blue
6949     * @param a a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for alpha/opacity
6950     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
6951     */
6952    public static float floatGet(float r, float g, float b, float a)
6953    {
6954        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor(((int)(a * 255) << 24) | ((int)(b * 255) << 16)
6955                | ((int)(g * 255) << 8) | (int)(r * 255));
6956    }

6958    /**
6959     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given an RGBA8888-format long. LibGDX expects ABGR format
6960     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
6961     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
6962     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
6963     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
6964     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
6965     * <br>
6966     * This method is probably not what you want unless you specifically have RGBA8888-format longs that you
6967     * want converted to packed floats. You probably should look at {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)} if
6968     * you have alpha and/or float components, or {@link #floatGetI(int, int, int)} for the common case of the 3 RGB
6969     * components as ints and alpha simply opaque.
6970     * @param c a long with format {@code 32 unused bits, 8 red bits, 8 green bits, 8 blue bits, 7 alpha bits, 1 unused bit}
6971     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
6972     */
6973    public static float floatGet(long c)
6974    {
6975        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor((int)((c >>> 24 & 0xff) | (c >>> 8 & 0xff00) | (c << 8 & 0xff0000)
6976                | (c << 24 & 0xfe000000)));
6977    }

6979    /**
6980     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given an RGBA8888-format int. LibGDX expects ABGR format
6981     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
6982     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
6983     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
6984     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
6985     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
6986     * <br>
6987     * This method is probably not what you want unless you specifically have RGBA8888-format ints that you
6988     * want converted to packed floats. You probably should look at {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)} if
6989     * you have alpha and/or float components, or {@link #floatGetI(int, int, int)} for the common case of the 3 RGB
6990     * components as ints and alpha simply opaque.
6991     * @param c an int with format {@code 8 red bits, 8 green bits, 8 blue bits, 7 alpha bits, 1 unused bit}
6992     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
6993     */
6994    public static float floatGet(int c)
6995    {
6996        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor((c >>> 24 & 0xff) | (c >>> 8 & 0xff00) | (c << 8 & 0xff0000)
6997                | (c << 24 & 0xfe000000));
6998    }

7000    /**
7001     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 3 RGB int components, setting alpha to opaque. LibGDX
7002     * expects ABGR format in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR,
7003     * or ARGB. Generally, packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed
7004     * directly to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate
7005     * objects. SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
7006     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
7007     * @param r an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for red
7008     * @param g an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for green
7009     * @param b an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for blue
7010     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
7011     */
7012    public static float floatGetI(int r, int g, int b)
7013    {
7014        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor((r & 0xff) | (g << 8 & 0xff00) | (b << 16 & 0xff0000)
7015                | 0xfe000000); //rgbToFloatColor((b & 0xff) | (g << 8 & 0xff00) | (r << 16));
7016    }

7018    @SuppressWarnings("NumericOverflow")
7019    public static float lerpFloatColors(final float start, final float end, final float change)
7020    {
7021        final int s = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(start), e = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(end),
7022                rs = (s & 255), gs = (s & 255 << 8) >>> 8, bs = (s & 255 << 16) >>> 16, as = (s & 254 << 24) >>> 24,
7023                re = (e & 255), ge = (e & 255 << 8) >>> 8, be = (e & 255 << 16) >>> 16, ae = (e & 254 << 24) >>> 24;
7024        return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(((int)(rs + change * (re - rs)) & 0xff)
7025                | ((int)(gs + change * (ge - gs)) & 0xff) << 8
7026                | (((int)(bs + change * (be - bs)) & 0xff) << 16)
7027                | (((int)(as + change * (ae - as)) & 0xfe) << 24));
7028    }

7030    /**
7031     * Similar to {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)}, but meant for an initial state before you have FOV or color
7032     * data to fill the lighting with, and you just need a map of a specific size that starts with no lighting. This
7033     * will produce a map that has white as the lighting color for all cells, but no cells will be lit. It is likely you
7034     * will want to pass this as basis to {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])}.
7035     * @param width the width of the colored lighting area to generate
7036     * @param height the height of the colored lighting area to generate
7037     * @return the colored lighting 3D float array, with no cells lit and all colors set to white
7038     */
7039    public static float[][][] blankColoredLighting(int width, int height)
7040    {
7041        return new float[][][]
7042                {
7043                        new float[width][height],
7044                        ArrayTools.fill(-0x1.fffffep126f, width, height)
7045                };
7046    }
7047
7048    /**
7049     * Removes any information from the given 3D float array for colored lighting, making it as if it had just been
7050     * built by {@link #blankColoredLighting(int, int)}, but without any allocations. This blank state is different from
7051     * being simply filled with all 0 or all default values; the two sub-arrays receive different contents (the one that
7052     * stores brightness is all 0, the one that stores colors will be filled with the float that encodes white).
7053     * @param original a 3d float array used for colored lighting; will be modified to be completely blank
7054     * @return original, after modification
7055     */
7056    public static float[][][] eraseColoredLighting(float[][][] original)
7057    {
7058        ArrayTools.fill(original[0], 0f);
7059        ArrayTools.fill(original[1], -0x1.fffffep126f);
7060        return original;
7061    }
7062    /**
7063     * Given a 2D double array that was probably produced by FOV and a packed color as a float, this gets a 3D float
7064     * array (really just two same-size 2D float arrays in one parent array) that stores the brightnesses in the first
7065     * 2D array element and the colors in the second 2D array element (using the given color if a cell has a value in
7066     * lights that is greater than 0, or defaulting to white if the cell is unlit). This has little use on its own, and
7067     * is meant to be given to {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])} so that multiple colors of lights
7068     * can be mixed.
7069     * @param lights a 2D double array that should probably come from FOV
7070     * @param color a packed float as produced by {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}
7071     * @return a 3D float array containing two 2D sub-arrays, the first holding brightness and the second holding color
7072     */
7073    public static float[][][] colorLighting(double[][] lights, float color)
7074    {
7075        return colorLightingInto(new float[2][lights.length][lights[0].length], lights, color);
7076    }
7077    /**
7078     * Given a 2D double array that was probably produced by FOV and a packed color as a float, this assigns into reuse
7079     * a 3D float array (really just two same-size 2D float arrays in one parent array) that stores the brightnesses in
7080     * the first 2D array element and the colors in the second 2D array element (using the given color if a cell has a
7081     * value in lights that is greater than 0, or defaulting to white if the cell is unlit). This method requires that
7082     * reuse has length of at least 2, where elements 0 and 1 must be 2D arrays of identical dimensions; this is the
7083     * format that {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)} produces. This has little use on its own, and  is meant to
7084     * be given to {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])} so that multiple colors of lights can be mixed.
7085     * @param reuse
7086     *              a 3D float array of the exact format produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)} or
7087     *              {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])}, and must have length 2; will be modified!
7088     * @param lights a 2D double array that should probably come from FOV
7089     * @param color a packed float as produced by {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}
7090     * @return reuse after modification
7091     */
7092    public static float[][][] colorLightingInto(float[][][] reuse, double[][] lights, float color)
7093    {
7094        for (int x = 0; x < lights.length; x++) {
7095            for (int y = 0; y < lights[0].length; y++) {
7096                reuse[1][x][y] = ((reuse[0][x][y] = (float) lights[x][y]) > 0f)
7097                        ? color
7098                        : -0x1.fffffep126f; // the color white as a float
7099            }
7100        }
7101        return reuse;
7102    }
7103
7104    /**
7105     * Adds two 3D arrays produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)} or this method and modifies the basis
7106     * parameter so it contains the combined brightnesses and colors of basis and other, in a pair of 2D arrays.
7107     * @param basis a 3D float array holding two 2D sub-arrays, as produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)}; will be modified!
7108     * @param other a 3D float array holding two 2D sub-arrays, as produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)}; will not be modified
7109     * @return basis, after modification; it can be passed to this method as basis again
7110     */
7111    public static float[][][] mixColoredLighting(float[][][] basis, float[][][] other)
7112    {
7113        int w = basis[0].length, h = basis[0][0].length;
7114        for (int x = 0; x < w && x < w; x++) {
7115            for (int y = 0; y < h && y < h; y++) {
7116                basis[1][x][y] = (basis[1][x][y] == -0x1.fffffep126f) // white as float
7117                        ? other[1][x][y]
7118                        : (other[1][x][y] == -0x1.fffffep126f) // white as float
7119                        ? basis[1][x][y]
7120                        : lerpFloatColors(basis[1][x][y], other[1][x][y], (other[0][x][y] - basis[0][x][y]) * 0.5f + 0.5f);
7121                basis[0][x][y] = Math.min(1.0f, basis[0][x][y] + other[0][x][y]);
7122            }
7123        }
7124        return basis;
7125    }
7126
7127
7128    @Override
7129    public String toString() {
7130        return name + " " + super.toString();
7131    }
7132
7133    public String getName() {
7134        return name;
7135    }
7136
7137    @Override
7138    public boolean equals(Object other) {
7139        return (other instanceof SColor || other instanceof Color) && toIntBits() == ((Color) other).toIntBits();
7140    }
7141
7142    @Override
7143    public int hashCode() {
7144        return  (155 + CrossHash.Wisp.hash(name)) * 31 + toIntBits();
7145    }
7146}
